  "prompt": "What is the salary of various elected representatives in India?",
  "response": "As of my last update, here are the basic salaries and entitlements for various elected representatives in India. These figures can change, so it's always a good idea to check the latest information from official sources.\n\n1. **Members of Parliament (MPs)**:\n   - Basic Salary: \u20b91,00,000 per month.\n   - Additional allowances (such as constituency allowances, office allowances, etc.) can increase their monthly earnings significantly.\n   - They are also entitled to various perks such as accommodation, travel allowances, and other benefits.\n\n2. **State Legislative Assembly Members (MLAs)**:\n   - Basic Salary: Varies by state, but generally ranges from \u20b960,000 to \u20b91,00,000 per month, depending on the state legislation.\n   - Similar to MPs, MLAs also receive allowances for constituency work, travel, and other benefits.\n\n3. **Chief Ministers**:\n   - Basic Salary: Varies from state to state but typically ranges from \u20b91,00,000 to \u20b92,00,000 per month.\n   - They also receive several allowances and benefits associated with the office.\n\n4. **Ministers (in both the Centre and State)**:\n   - Basic Salary: Generally similar to MPs and MLAs, depending on whether they are central or state ministers, usually around \u20b91,00,000 per month plus allowances.\n   \n5. **Panchayati Raj Representatives**:\n   - Salaries for these positions (such as Sarpanch or Panchayat members) can vary significantly across states and are generally much lower than those of MPs or MLAs. It can be anywhere from \u20b95,000 to \u20b930,000 per month depending on the state and the specific position.\n\nThese figures represent basic salaries and can exclude various allowances, which can be substantial depending on the role and responsibilities. Always refer to the latest government regulations and updates for the most accurate and current information.",
